\subtree{
\title{Successes and failures}


\subtree{
\title{Success}

\p{The main points of success were in the application of the orthogonality closure
conditions, for example in [showing left and right fibrations are inner](stt-00C7),
or that [simplicial types are triangulated](stt-00CS). See for example:
}

\transclude{stt-00C7}

\p{
This proof seems to have a number of advantages over the more nuts and bolts
approach in e.g. the original work on STT \citek{RS17}: It has a very natural
extension to showing all that left-fibrations are right orthogonal to the
left-horns (which I hope to formalise soon); it dualises almost trivially and it
formalises surprisingly nicely - particularly important in the setting without strict
extension types. Thanks again to [Freddie](fredrikbakke) for pointing out the
power of these conditions and showing me some of these arguments when we talked
recently.
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Failure}
\p{I made some attempt at proving the following proposition: }


\subtree[stt-00CZ]{
\taxon{Proposition}

\p{A [simplicial](stt-00AC) type #{A} is [a precategory](stt-00AI) if
and only if for every #{x : A}, the family #{\Hom(-,x)} is [covariant](stt-00AY).}
}

\p{But the argument given in \citet{8.13}{RS17} is significantly more fiddly
to prove in the our setting compared to in a type theory with a strict shape layer
and extension types. Instead of persevering, I decided to postpone this endeavour
- hoping that something nicer like the above might come along. And I have had
[some thoughts in this direction](https://github.com/samtoth/agda-synthetic-categories/issues/43) but it remains to be seen how or if it will work out.}
}
}
